{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_011vDtCd3xLNJGnkULHvVcBz","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Ansible AI Helpers Strategy — 2026-06-17\n2\t\n3\tStrategy session on integrating the UXD AI Helpers repo with Ansible's Carbonite harness. First major external consumer of the centralized skill distribution model.\n4\t\n5\t## Attendees\n6\t\n7\tJeremy Perry, Mike Franke, Nicole Thoen, Jeff Puzzo, Cate Ferman, Leslie Hinson, Andy Braren, Melissa Grimes (invited: Taufique Rahman)\n8\t\n9\t## Context\n10\t\n11\t- Ansible uses **Carbonite** as their AI harness, managed by the **ATT team** (thinly veiled Star Wars reference)\n12\t- Jeff Puzzo and Nicole Thoen have been working with the Carbonite team on PatternFly integration — PatternFly is already in Carbonite's internal AI marketplace\n13\t- A readout with Ansible leadership the previous week surfaced interest in a **heuristic evaluation skill** as a concrete example of UX expertise\n14\t- Tracy (UXD leadership) advised the team to bring an opinionated point of view — not just \"here are skills\" but \"here's how UXD recommends using them\"\n15\t\n16\t## Key Decisions\n17\t\n18\t### 1. Heuristic Eval Selected as Pilot\n19\tThe [heuristic evaluation skill](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) was selected as the initial pilot to demonstrate AI Helpers integration with Carbonite. Cate Ferman will coordinate a 2-3 session pilot with Ansible design and research teams to validate recommendations before broader rollout. Questions about guardrails, cadence, and usage guidelines are deferred until after pilot validation.\n20\t\n21\t### 2. Centralized Repo Integration via MRs\n22\tNicole Thoen was firm: skills must flow through the AI Helpers repo via merge requests, not ad-hoc downloads. This preserves UXD ownership and distribution control. If teams pull skills locally and fork them, \"they're not ours anymore.\" Jira tickets will track integration progress and give external teams visibility into timelines.\n23\t\n24\t### 3. June 30 Presentation to Ansible Leadership\n25\tJeremy Perry secured a 30-minute slot with Kevin (Ansible technical leadership) and his staff. The pitch: UXD's opinionated design pipeline (\"the purple box\") — not just access to skills, but a recommended way of working. Key contacts on the Ansible side: Tim Puyer and Nathan Weatherly (global engineering working group).\n26\t\n27\t## The \"Purple Box\" Discussion\n28\t\n29\tTracy raised an important framing question: teams shouldn't just get access to skills — they need UXD's point of view on how to use them effectively within their workflows. This is the [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md) in practice. The challenge: each product team's orchestrator is different (Carbonite for Ansible, something else for OCP), so the mechanism for consuming skills varies even if the skills themselves are maintained centrally.\n30\t\n31\t## Scaling Concerns\n32\t\n33\tNicole and Mike acknowledged the maintenance burden: per-orchestrator integration means each new product team is \"square one\" for wiring. OCP's Matt Carlton already reached out about getting skills into their AISDLC. Possible model: UXD people embedded in each product space own the orchestrator-specific integration while central team maintains the skills.\n34\t\n35\tJeff proposed filling workflow gaps proactively — identify what Ansible's harness is missing, show up with a working solution, and create \"I want that\" moments rather than asking teams what they want.\n36\t\n37\t## Next Steps\n38\t\n39\t| Owner | Action |\n40\t|---|---|\n41\t| Melissa Grimes | Submit MR to add heuristic eval skill into AI Helpers repo |\n42\t| Jeff Puzzo | Configure technical connection between Carbonite and AI Helpers repo |\n43\t| Nicole Thoen | Create Jira tickets for AI Helpers integration (visibility for Ansible team) |\n44\t| Jeremy Perry + Mike Franke | Coordinate follow-up meeting next week |\n45\t| Cate Ferman + Nick Lemon | Prepare pilot plan presentation for Ansible team |\n46\t\n47\t## Internship Connection\n48\t\n49\tThis meeting directly demonstrates the UXD skill distribution model that the [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md) describes. The heuristic eval pilot connects to the same [Nielsen's Heuristics](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) methodology from Evan's first internship task. The [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) patterns (eval.yaml, judges, automated scoring) will likely inform how pilot results are measured. The [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) pipeline is a natural next candidate for Ansible integration after the heuristic eval pilot proves the distribution model.\n50\t\n51\t## Related\n52\t\n53\t- [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md) — the \"purple box\" opinionated pipeline being pitched to Ansible\n54\t- [Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) — the heuristic eval skill selected as pilot\n55\t- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — evaluation patterns relevant to pilot measurement\n56\t- [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) — next candidate for Ansible integration\n57\t- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — automated evaluation connects to the heuristic eval pilot\n58\t- [My Cursor Claw](my-cursor-claw.md) — the AI helpers repo and skills being distributed\n59\t- [WG: UXD Efficiency — June 29](wg-uxd-efficiency-2026-06-29.md) — continuation of Ansible integration work, AI helpers as primary vetted skills source\n60\t- [AI Helpers Repo Strategy Update — 2026-07-02](ai-helpers-repo-slack-2026-07-02.md) — Slack follow-up confirming skill directory structure, versioning, and eval config policy\n61\t\n62\t## Sources\n63\t\n64\t- ~/Desktop/Notes Inbox/gemini-2026-06-17-sharing-ai-helpers-strategy-with-ansible---20260617-1329-edt---notes-by-gemini.txt\n65\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a6cd2b8-e97e-4155-bee0-36a73a1fd425","uuid":"98062c21-4461-4b08-b74b-f1fc3d06669e","timestamp":"2026-07-09T16:06:31.881Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/ansible-ai-helpers-strategy-2026-06-17.md","content":"# Ansible AI Helpers Strategy — 2026-06-17\n\nStrategy session on integrating the UXD AI Helpers repo with Ansible's Carbonite harness. First major external consumer of the centralized skill distribution model.\n\n## Attendees\n\nJeremy Perry, Mike Franke, Nicole Thoen, Jeff Puzzo, Cate Ferman, Leslie Hinson, Andy Braren, Melissa Grimes (invited: Taufique Rahman)\n\n## Context\n\n- Ansible uses **Carbonite** as their AI harness, managed by the **ATT team** (thinly veiled Star Wars reference)\n- Jeff Puzzo and Nicole Thoen have been working with the Carbonite team on PatternFly integration — PatternFly is already in Carbonite's internal AI marketplace\n- A readout with Ansible leadership the previous week surfaced interest in a **heuristic evaluation skill** as a concrete example of UX expertise\n- Tracy (UXD leadership) advised the team to bring an opinionated point of view — not just \"here are skills\" but \"here's how UXD recommends using them\"\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n### 1. Heuristic Eval Selected as Pilot\nThe [heuristic evaluation skill](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) was selected as the initial pilot to demonstrate AI Helpers integration with Carbonite. Cate Ferman will coordinate a 2-3 session pilot with Ansible design and research teams to validate recommendations before broader rollout. Questions about guardrails, cadence, and usage guidelines are deferred until after pilot validation.\n\n### 2. Centralized Repo Integration via MRs\nNicole Thoen was firm: skills must flow through the AI Helpers repo via merge requests, not ad-hoc downloads. This preserves UXD ownership and distribution control. If teams pull skills locally and fork them, \"they're not ours anymore.\" Jira tickets will track integration progress and give external teams visibility into timelines.\n\n### 3. June 30 Presentation to Ansible Leadership\nJeremy Perry secured a 30-minute slot with Kevin (Ansible technical leadership) and his staff. The pitch: UXD's opinionated design pipeline (\"the purple box\") — not just access to skills, but a recommended way of working. Key contacts on the Ansible side: Tim Puyer and Nathan Weatherly (global engineering working group).\n\n## The \"Purple Box\" Discussion\n\nTracy raised an important framing question: teams shouldn't just get access to skills — they need UXD's point of view on how to use them effectively within their workflows. This is the [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md) in practice. The challenge: each product team's orchestrator is different (Carbonite for Ansible, something else for OCP), so the mechanism for consuming skills varies even if the skills themselves are maintained centrally.\n\n## Scaling Concerns\n\nNicole and Mike acknowledged the maintenance burden: per-orchestrator integration means each new product team is \"square one\" for wiring. OCP's Matt Carlton already reached out about getting skills into their AISDLC. Possible model: UXD people embedded in each product space own the orchestrator-specific integration while central team maintains the skills.\n\nJeff proposed filling workflow gaps proactively — identify what Ansible's harness is missing, show up with a working solution, and create \"I want that\" moments rather than asking teams what they want.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n| Owner | Action |\n|---|---|\n| Melissa Grimes | Submit MR to add heuristic eval skill into AI Helpers repo |\n| Jeff Puzzo | Configure technical connection between Carbonite and AI Helpers repo |\n| Nicole Thoen | Create Jira tickets for AI Helpers integration (visibility for Ansible team) |\n| Jeremy Perry + Mike Franke | Coordinate follow-up meeting next week |\n| Cate Ferman + Nick Lemon | Prepare pilot plan presentation for Ansible team |\n\n## Internship Connection\n\nThis meeting directly demonstrates the UXD skill distribution model that the [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md) describes. The heuristic eval pilot connects to the same [Nielsen's Heuristics](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) methodology from Evan's first internship task. The [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) patterns (eval.yaml, judges, automated scoring) will likely inform how pilot results are measured. The [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) pipeline is a natural next candidate for Ansible integration after the heuristic eval pilot proves the distribution model.\n\n## Related\n\n- [AI-SDLC Pipeline](ai-sdlc-pipeline.md) — the \"purple box\" opinionated pipeline being pitched to Ansible\n- [Nielsen's Heuristics & The Jagged Edge](nielsens-heuristics-jagged-edge.md) — the heuristic eval skill selected as pilot\n- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — evaluation patterns relevant to pilot measurement\n- [Prototype Creator](prototype-creator.md) — next candidate for Ansible integration\n- [Evaluator Super Agent](evaluator-super-agent.md) — automated evaluation connects to the heuristic eval pilot\n- [My Cursor Claw](my-cursor-claw.md) — the AI helpers repo and skills being distributed\n- [WG: UXD Efficiency — June 29](wg-uxd-efficiency-2026-06-29.md) — continuation of Ansible integration work, AI helpers as primary vetted skills source\n- [AI Helpers Repo Strategy Update — 2026-07-02](ai-helpers-repo-slack-2026-07-02.md) — Slack follow-up confirming skill directory structure, versioning, and eval config policy\n\n## Sources\n\n- ~/Desktop/Notes Inbox/gemini-2026-06-17-sharing-ai-helpers-strategy-with-ansible---20260617-1329-edt---notes-by-gemini.txt\n","numLines":65,"startLine":1,"totalLines":65}}}
